snippet.textDisplay: This is what I call the “Human Effect”. It states that no matter how different you try to make your world, it will always have elements of earth or humans in it. This is caused by a number of processes in your brain when creating ideas. This is ok though, having relatable settings, and/or characters, and/or story is a key part in keeping your viewer interested. So while you wish your world could be just a bit more diverse, it’s safer to keep some themes of humanity in your stories.

snippet.textDisplay:
The problem with this theory begins with your discussion on the big dipper/ursa major. When I was younger, I was in Boy Scouts so I know a bit about navigation using the stars. You can find the North star using the big dipper. The 2 stars at the the end of the big dipper's cup, Merak and Dubhe point to the north star. Also the North star is about 4 times the seen length between Merak and Dubhe so you can find Polaris by using 2 fingers and simply counting to 3.
In the Legend of Zelda sky, while the big dipper may exist, the little dipper and North Star do not. Not only that, if you were to look in the direction where Polaris should than see which direction you are facing you will find that it isn't North.
A potential solution: The infinite universe theroy. It is likely that Hyrule takes place in another universe than our own. The big piece of evidence that supports this is the thing created with the creation of Hyrule: the Triforce.
If something like the Triforce existed on earth, you could bet that there would be huge wars over this thing. While some of the magic in Hyrule can be explained as advanced technology, the one thing that cannot be is the Triforce. The Triforce can grant any wish, meaning you can wish to create or destroy things. This directly contradicts the Law of Physics saying that: matter cannot be created or destroyed. The laws of physics are universal, but that means that throughout our universe that the laws are true. Because this law can be broken it means Hyrule must exist in another universe.
The next piece of evidence supporting my idea is your star idea. Through the infinite universe theory, it is infinitely likely that and an infinite number of Hyrule universes have some of the same constalations as earth. This is infinite likelihood so it kinda has to be true according to the infinite universe theory.
Lastly comes the formation of Hyrule. The story goes that the three golden goddesses, Din. Nayru, and Farore created the land and as the three left they created the Triforce. We know this story to be true in the Zelda universe/universes because of the existence of the Triforce in the games. The problem with this story existing on earth is what Farore did. She created life to uphold the law Nayru created. We have scientific evidence that life did not exist on earth for almost a billion years.
